:INFO
What Each Part Does
Every part in a mechanical keyboard build affects the final feel and sound \
differently. Understanding the role of each one helps you make better \
buying decisions.

:INFO
The Case
The outer shell that holds everything together. Aluminum cases have a \
heavier, more premium feel. Plastic cases are lighter and often have more \
flex. Acrylic lets you see the PCB and RGB lighting.

:INFO
The PCB
The brain of the keyboard. It reads each keypress and sends it to your \
computer. Hot swap PCBs have sockets so you can change switches without \
soldering. This is essential for a first build.

:INFO
Switches
The mechanism under each key. Linear switches move smoothly with no bump \
or click. Tactile switches have a noticeable bump at the actuation point. \
Clicky switches add an audible click. Start linear if you are unsure.

:INFO
Stabilizers
Large keys like spacebar, shift, backspace, and enter need stabilizers to \
prevent wobble. Lubing them before assembly is the single highest impact \
upgrade in any budget build.

:INFO
Keycaps
The plastic caps that sit on top of each switch. PBT plastic is harder and \
more resistant to shine from fingertip oils. ABS plastic feels smoother \
but wears visibly over months of heavy use.
